05222nam a22007815i 9781641892186DE-B159720210621102733.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||210621t20192019xxk    fo  d z      eng d  a97816418921867 a10.1515/97816418921862doi  a(DE-B1597)546341  a(OCoLC)1128412727  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  axxkcGB-LDS 7aHIS0370102bisacsh04a641.231 aPhillips, Noëlle, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aCraft Beer Culture and Modern Medievalism :bBrewing Dissent /cNoëlle Phillips. 1aLeeds : bArc Humanities Press, c[2019] 4c©2019  a1 online resource (164 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aCollection Development, Cultural Heritage, and Digital Humanities00tFrontmatter -- tCONTENTS -- tList of Illustrations -- tAcknowledgements -- tChapter 1. Introduction: Medievalism and Craft Beer -- tChapter 2. Reading Beer in the Middle Ages -- tChapter 3. Resistance and Revolution: Craft Beer versus Corporate Giants -- tChapter 4. Beer Heroes and Monastic Medievalism -- tChapter 5. Militant Medievalism: Norsemen, Mythology, and Masculinity -- tChapter 6. Pale Ales and White Knights: Craft Brewing, Whiteness, and Medievalism -- tChapter 7. Conclusion: The Alchemy of Alcohol -- tSelect Bibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aSince the 1970s, the craft brewing industry has grown in popularity. However, with the introduction of the Internet and the consequent globalization of cultures and economies, craft beer marketing has increasingly evoked the medieval past in order to appeal to our collective sense of a lost community, and even a lost purity. This book discusses the desire for the local, the non-corporate, and the pre-modern in the discourse of craft brewing, which has become a form of ideological resistance to corporate capitalism, forming a strong counter-cultural narrative. However, such discourses also reinforce colonial histories of purity and conquest while effacing indigenous voices, and there are troubling intersections between the desire for a medieval past and the desire to preserve the imaginary "whiteness" of that past. Such considerations are particularly relevant now, during a time in which white nationalist groups (many of which turn to a medieval past for inspiration) are increasing in influence and visibility. Moving from beer in the Middle Ages to beer in 2019, this book deploys analysis of literary and historical texts, advertisements, labels, and interviews with craft brewers and writers to argue that craft beer is much more than a delicious drink and a social connector; its marketing, its appeal, and its ubiquitous presence in middle class North America reveals a powerful cultural desire for the past in a world that privileges the present.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 21. Jun 2021) 7aHISTORY / Medieval.2bisacsh  aCraft beer.  abrewing.  acultural appropriation.  amedievalism.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertDG Plus PP Package 2020 Part 2z978311069629508iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2019 Englishz978311061076508iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2019z9783110664232oZDB-23-DGG08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE History 2019 Englishz978311061017808iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE History 2019z9783110606195oZDB-23-DEG08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertPP ROW Ebook Package English 2020z978311069630140uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9781641892186zCo-access DOI >> click Walter de Gruyter40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781641892186423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9781641892186.jpg  a978-3-11-061017-8  EB